'''Rodrigo Paz Delgado''' is an [[Ecuador]]ian politician and businessman. He was the mayor of [[Quito]] from 1988 to 1992.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=7ChY2I6D6j0C&pg=PA83&dq=%22Rodrigo+Paz%22+mayor&hl=en&ei=OsqUTc_hKMLj4Aam2KGDDA&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=3&ved=0CDMQ6AEwAg#v=onepage&q=%22Rodrigo%20Paz%22%20mayor&f=false|last=Gerlach|first=Allen|title=Indians, oil, and politics: a recent history of Ecuador|publisher=Rowman & Littlefield|year=2003|isbn=978-0-8420-5108-8}}</ref> He ran as a presidential candidate in 1995/6.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=M_oaAAAAIBAJ&sjid=v0cEAAAAIBAJ&pg=4331,1796828&dq=rodrigo-paz+mayor&hl=en|last=Hayes|first=Monty|title=Ecuador holds elections as economy stagnates|work=[[The Daily News (Kentucky)|The Daily News]]|date=17 May 1996}}</ref> One of his political parties was [[Democracia Popular]] (DP).<ref>Gerlach (2003) [https://books.google.com/books?id=7ChY2I6D6j0C&pg=PA83&dq=%22Rodrigo+Paz%22+mayor&hl=en&ei=OsqUTc_hKMLj4Aam2KGDDA&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=3&ved=0CDMQ6AEwAg#v=onepage&q=%22Rodrigo%20Paz%22%20mayor&f=false p.83]</ref>

Paz served for a time as the Finance Minister of Ecuador.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://select.nytimes.com/gst/abstract.html?res=F70814F93F550C7A8DDDAA0894D1494D81|last=Rohter|first=Larry|authorlink=Larry Rohter|title=Ecuadorean Concessions Win Support for Austerity Measures|work=[[New York Times]]|date=19 March 1999}}</ref> He has been the principal director [[Liga Deportiva Universitaria de Quito]] since 1997, but has been involved with the club since 1959.{{Citation needed|date=March 2011}}

